84","1295":"1295","1360":"1360","1370":"1370","1282":"1282","1290":"1290","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1401":"1401","1345":"1345","1234":"1234","1399":"1399","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","about 1334":"circa 1334","about 1300":"circa 1300","about 1330":"circa 1330","1319":"1319","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Hempstead, Essex, England":"Hempstead, Essex, England","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","of Kent,England":"Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Kennington, Kent, England":"Kennington, Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1282–about 1360":"about 1282–about 1360","1282–1360":"1282–1360","1295–1370":"1295–1370","1300–1345":"1300–1345","1319–1399":"1319–1399","1330–1401":"1330–1401","1234–1284":"1234–1284","about 1282":"about 1282","about 1360":"about 1360","5 April 1345":"5 April 1345","1330":"1330","1284":"1284","1295":"1295","1360":"1360","1370":"1370","1282":"1282","1290":"1290","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1401":"1401","1345":"1345","1234":"1234","1399":"1399","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","about 1334":"about 1334","about 1300":"about 1300","about 1330":"about 1330","1319":"1319","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Hempstead, Essex, England":"Hempstead, Essex, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","of Kent,England":"Kent, England, United Kingdom","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Kennington, Kent, England":"Kennington, Kent, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Belknap","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: probably a habitational name from a lost or unidentified place, the second element of which is most likely Middle English <i>knappe</i> ‘hilltop’. Compare   Belnap  .","History: Abraham Belknap (<i>c.</i> 1588–<i>c.</i> 1643) emigrated from Latton, Essex, England, to Lynn, MA, in the 1630s."],"variants":[{"name":"Belnap","meanings":["English: variant of   Belknap  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":8,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705191,"age":33,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705192,"age":46,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705193,"age":55,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Robert John Belknap was born about 1282, in Hempstead, Essex, England as the son of Robert Belknappe. He married Lady Alice de Seagrave about 1334. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. He died about 1360, in Kent, England, at the age of 80."},"et":{"about 1282–about 1360":"umbes 1282–umbes 1360","1282–1360":"1282–1360","1295–1370":"1295–1370","1300–1345":"1300–1345","1319–1399":"1319–1399","1330–1401":"1330–1401","1234–1284":"1234–1284","about 1282":"umbes 1282","about 1360":"umbes 1360","5 April 1345":"5. aprill 1345","1330":"1330","1284":"1284","1295":"1295","1360":"1360","1370":"1370","1282":"1282","1290":"1290","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1401":"1401","1345":"1345","1234":"1234","1399":"1399","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","about 1334":"umbes 1334","about 1300":"umbes 1300","about 1330":"umbes 1330","1319":"1319","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Hempstead, Essex, England":"Hempstead, Essex, England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","of Kent,England":"Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Kennington, Kent, England":"Kennington, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1282–about 1360":"noin 1282–noin 1360","1282–1360":"1282–1360","1295–1370":"1295–1370","1300–1345":"1300–1345","1319–1399":"1319–1399","1330–1401":"1330–1401","1234–1284":"1234–1284","about 1282":"noin 1282","about 1360":"noin 1360","5 April 1345":"5. huhtikuuta 1345","1330":"1330","1284":"1284","1295":"1295","1360":"1360","1370":"1370","1282":"1282","1